const faqs = [
  {
    q: "Who owns Frigidaire? Is it still American?",
    a: "Frigidaire is owned by Electrolux, the Swedish home-appliance group, which acquired the brand from White Consolidated Industries in 1986. Most Frigidaire-branded appliances sold in the US are still designed and assembled domestically, major US manufacturing is in Anderson, South Carolina (refrigerators); Memphis, Tennessee (cooking); Springfield, Tennessee (dishwashers); and Augusta, Georgia (laundry). The brand has been around since 1918 (originally Guardian Frigerator Company in Indiana, then acquired by GM, then sold to White, then to Electrolux), making it one of the oldest American appliance brand names in continuous use. From a service standpoint, Electrolux ownership has stabilized the parts supply and engineering investment, especially on the Gallery premium tier."
  },
  {
    q: "What's the difference between Frigidaire, Frigidaire Gallery, and Frigidaire Professional?",
    a: "Three tiers, increasing in feature density and price. Frigidaire (base line), value-tier appliances at competitive price points; reliable workhorses, no design pretense, the brand's broadest US distribution. Frigidaire Gallery, premium consumer tier with better controls, better fit-and-finish, Wi-Fi connectivity on newer models, and stainless-steel finishes standard. Frigidaire Professional, the top tier, positioned to compete with KitchenAid Pro and select luxury lines; pro-style range hardware, premium refrigeration, integrated cooking suites. The Professional line has been narrowed in the 2020s with some categories discontinued or rolled into the broader Gallery line, but service is still active for in-warranty and out-of-warranty Professional units across our service area."
  },
  {
    q: "Why does my Frigidaire ice maker keep failing?",
    a: "Three causes account for the bulk of Frigidaire ice maker calls. (1) Water inlet valve failure, the dual-coil solenoid valve that feeds the ice maker fatigues over years of cycling. Symptoms: no ice production, very slow ice production, or water leaking inside the freezer compartment. Replacement $185-$285. (2) Ice maker module / motor / optics fault, Frigidaire's modular ice maker assemblies (most common: 5303918344 and 241798231) have a typical 5-7 year service life on average use. Replacement $245-$385. (3) Mineral buildup from LA's hard water clogging the fill tube or valve screens, particularly common in the Inland Empire and parts of the San Fernando Valley where water hardness runs higher. Mineral cleanup is a 30-minute job; we descale the inlet path and verify normal flow. About 25% of LA-area Frigidaire ice maker calls trace to mineral buildup as the primary or secondary issue."
  },
  {
    q: "What does an E10 / E20 / E70 / EF1 error mean on my Frigidaire washer or dryer?",
    a: "Frigidaire's E-series and EF-series error codes are some of the most direct in the appliance industry. E10, water isn't entering the machine; check the water-supply taps, hoses, and inlet valve. E20, water isn't draining; the drain pump, drain hose, or filter is the issue. E30, drum overfilled; usually a stuck water-inlet solenoid or a level-sensor fault. E70, cold water isn't entering specifically (the hot supply is OK); split inlet valve issue. EF1, drain pump fault on Frigidaire dryers (specifically condenser dryers); usually a clogged drain pump or sensor. EF0 / EF2, over-sudsing detection (use less detergent, switch to HE if you haven't). Diagnostic order on any E-code: full power cycle (5 minutes off), confirm water supply taps are open, check the filter at the bottom front of the unit. About 30% of E-codes resolve at the homeowner-troubleshooting layer at no parts cost."
  },
  {
    q: "Are Frigidaire appliances reliable? Should I keep mine or replace?",
    a: "Honest answer depends on the category. Frigidaire refrigerators are middle-of-the-pack reliability, solid through year 8-10, then control-board and ice-maker failures climb. Top-freezer Frigidaire models (FFTR, FFHT series) are the most reliable category in the lineup; budget-tier French Door and Side-by-Side models have higher failure rates than competitors at similar price points. Frigidaire freezers (FFFH, FFFC, FFFU stand-up and chest models) are excellent, long service life, mostly mechanical, easy to repair. Frigidaire ranges and ovens are competitive in their price band. Frigidaire dishwashers in the value tier have a documented pattern of control-panel failures and motor wear at year 6-8; Gallery dishwashers run notably better. Frigidaire laundry is mid-tier, adequate, not standout. Repair-vs-replace at year 12+ tilts toward replacement on most Frigidaire categories; under year 8, repair is usually the right call."
  },
  {
    q: "Do you carry Frigidaire OEM parts on the truck?",
    a: "Yes, Frigidaire common wear items are stocked on our trucks: refrigerator door gaskets, ice maker assemblies, water inlet valves, evaporator fan motors; dishwasher drain pumps, water inlet valves, control panels (the documented value-tier weakness); washer drain pumps, lid switches, drive belts; dryer thermal fuses, thermistors, drum belts, idler pulleys, heating elements; range surface igniters (gas), bake/broil elements (electric), oven temperature sensors. Less common parts, main control boards, specific Frigidaire Professional components, freezer-specific parts on older FFFH/FFFC models, come from authorized Electrolux distribution, usually 1-3 day lead. Several budget-tier Frigidaire models carry distinctive small-batch parts that occasionally have longer lead times; we confirm parts availability and timing on the diagnostic visit before quoting."
  },
  {
    q: "How much does Frigidaire appliance repair cost in LA?",
    a: "Diagnostic is $89, applied toward the repair when work is approved. Common Frigidaire repairs: refrigerator door gasket $180-$280; refrigerator water inlet valve $185-$285; refrigerator ice maker assembly $245-$385; refrigerator main control board $345-$525; refrigerator evaporator fan motor $245-$385; freezer defrost system $185-$345; washer lid switch / drain pump $145-$385; washer drive belt $185-$285; dryer thermal fuse + vent inspection $145-$245; dryer heating element $285-$425; dryer EF1 drain pump (condenser dryers) $245-$385; dishwasher drain pump $245-$385; dishwasher control panel $285-$445; range surface igniter $145-$215; oven bake element $185-$285; oven temperature sensor $145-$215. Frigidaire Gallery premium uplift: 10-15% above base. Frigidaire Professional premium uplift: 20-30% above base."
  },
