<!-- 01 INTRO -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">01, About this service</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">Frigidaire is one of the oldest American appliance names. Now Electrolux-owned, still US-built.</h2>

    <p>Frigidaire has been around since 1918, one of the longest continuously-used American appliance brand names. Through ownership transitions (originally Guardian Frigerator Company in Indiana, then GM, then White Consolidated Industries, then Electrolux since 1986), the brand has remained anchored in US manufacturing: Anderson, South Carolina for refrigerators; Memphis, Tennessee for cooking; Springfield, Tennessee for dishwashers; Augusta, Georgia for laundry. Electrolux's Swedish ownership has stabilized the parts supply chain and underwritten investment in the Gallery premium tier. From a homeowner's standpoint, Frigidaire is a US-built, US-serviced brand under European parent ownership, and the parts-and-service network reflects that stability.</p>

    <p>Two Frigidaire-specific service realities shape how we approach every call. First, the <strong>tier hierarchy</strong> matters more than on most brands: base Frigidaire is value-tier (built to a price point, with the failure-rate profile that implies); Frigidaire Gallery is the mid-premium tier with notably better fit-and-finish and longer service life; Frigidaire Professional is the top tier, narrowed in the 2020s with some categories rolled back into Gallery. Repair-vs-replace economics differ across the three. Second, <strong>LA's hard water</strong> drives a meaningful share of our Frigidaire refrigerator service mix, mineral buildup in ice maker fill tubes, water inlet valves, and dispenser systems is more common on Frigidaire's water-handling components than on some competitors. Inland Empire and parts of the San Fernando Valley see this fastest; Westside and coastal areas less so. We descale and clean as part of routine ice maker service.</p>

    <p>This page covers Frigidaire repair across all major appliance categories and all three tiers. Every service call gets a $89 residential diagnostic (applied toward the repair when work is approved), OEM parts where we can, and an honest written quote before any work begins.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 02 REFRIGERATOR -->
<section class="section section-gray">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-number">02, Frigidaire refrigerator &amp; freezer repair</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">Frigidaire refrigerators &amp; freezers, top-freezer workhorses, French Door + Side-by-Side, garage freezers.</h2>

    <p class="lead">Frigidaire's refrigeration lineup is broader than most realize, top-freezer FFTR and FFHT models that anchor the value tier, French Door (FRFG, GRFG Gallery), Side-by-Side (FRSS, GRSS Gallery), Counter-Depth, and a strong stand-alone freezer line (FFFH chest, FFFC stand-up, FFFU upright) that's particularly common in inland garages.</p>

    <p>Most-common Frigidaire refrigerator service items by year:</p>

    <ul class="bullet-list">
      <li><strong>Year 4-7, Ice maker assembly:</strong> Most common Frigidaire refrigerator service item. Modular assemblies (5303918344, 241798231 most common) have a 5-7 year typical service life. Mineral buildup from LA's hard water often accelerates failure on inland units. Replacement $245-$385.</li>
      <li><strong>Year 5-9, Water inlet valve:</strong> Dual-coil solenoid wear; partial fills, slow dispensing, or interior leaks. Replacement $185-$285. Often paired with ice maker service when both have aged together.</li>
      <li><strong>Year 6-10, Evaporator fan motor:</strong> Whirring or grinding sound from the freezer compartment, intermittent cooling. Replacement $245-$385.</li>
      <li><strong>Year 7-11, Defrost system:</strong> Heater, thermostat, or sensor failure causing frost buildup or no-cool. Diagnostic separates which component; $185-$345 replacement depending on item.</li>
      <li><strong>Year 8-12, Main control board:</strong> Less prone to failure than GE or some competitors but still a wear item, especially after grid power surges (common during SoCal summer heat-wave demand events). Replacement $345-$525.</li>
      <li><strong>Year 8-12, Door gasket:</strong> Especially in coastal homes (Malibu, Pacific Palisades, Newport Beach, Laguna). Replacement $180-$280.</li>
    </ul>

    <p>Frigidaire stand-alone freezers (FFFH chest, FFFC stand-up, FFFU upright) are one of the most reliable categories in the entire Frigidaire lineup, mostly mechanical, easy to service, long service life on average. Most calls trace to door gasket wear, defrost system on the auto-defrost models, or thermostat failure on older mechanical units. <strong>Garage-installed Frigidaire freezers in the Inland Empire</strong> see harder service life from summer ambient stress, temperatures in unconditioned garages routinely exceed 100°F in July and August, well outside spec for many freezer designs. Compressor stress accelerates and most garage-freezer service calls cluster in the August-September window. <a href="/brands/frigidaire-freezer-repair/">Frigidaire freezer repair page →</a></p>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 03 LAUNDRY -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-number">03, Frigidaire laundry repair</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">Frigidaire washers and dryers, E-code and EF-code translation.</h2>

    <p class="lead">Frigidaire laundry is mid-tier reliability, adequate, not standout, but the diagnostic experience is one of the better in the industry because Frigidaire's E-series and EF-series error codes are notably direct: each code points to a specific subsystem rather than a generic "control board" trip. Most Frigidaire laundry service calls run faster than equivalent calls on brands with vaguer code systems.</p>

    <p>Most-common Frigidaire washer service items:</p>

    <ul class="bullet-list">
      <li><strong>Lid switch (top-load) or door lock (front-load):</strong> Year 3-6 typical. Won't start, won't enter spin, or stops mid-cycle. Replacement $145-$215.</li>
      <li><strong>Drain pump (E20 code):</strong> Won't drain; clothes left wet at end of cycle. Year 5-8. Replacement $245-$385.</li>
      <li><strong>Water inlet valve (E10 / E70 codes):</strong> Won't fill or won't fill cold water. Year 6-9. Replacement $185-$285.</li>
      <li><strong>Drive belt + motor pulley (top-load):</strong> Won't agitate or won't spin. Year 7-10. Replacement $185-$285.</li>
      <li><strong>Bearing service (front-load year 8-12):</strong> Grinding sound during spin cycles. Bearing + drum seal as a set, $585-$880 with labor.</li>
    </ul>

    <p>Frigidaire dryers are middle-of-the-pack reliability with one specific code worth noting. The <strong>EF1 error</strong> on Frigidaire condenser dryers indicates a drain pump fault, usually a clogged drain pump or a sensor issue. Standard Frigidaire dryer service items: thermal fuse blown from vent blockage (always inspect the vent before replacing the fuse, thermal fuse alone fails again within weeks if vent isn't cleared), heating element burnout at year 8-12, drum belt + idler pulley wear at year 6-9, thermistor drift causing intermittent heating. Gas dryers add gas valve coil failure mode at year 9-12.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 04 OTHER APPLIANCES -->
<section class="section section-gray">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-number">04, Other Frigidaire appliances</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">Frigidaire dishwashers, ranges, microwaves.</h2>

    <p class="lead">Frigidaire's appliance breadth covers most kitchen categories. Service depth varies meaningfully by tier, value-tier Frigidaire appliances have shorter service life and more frequent service calls than Gallery, and Professional sits at premium reliability when properly maintained.</p>

    <div class="appliance-grid">
      <div class="appliance-card">
        <h3>Frigidaire Dishwashers (FFBD, FGBD Gallery, FPID Professional)</h3>
        <p>Value-tier Frigidaire dishwashers (FFBD series) have a documented pattern of <strong>control panel failures</strong> at year 6-8, touch panel responsiveness degrades, buttons stop registering. Replacement $285-$445. Gallery dishwashers (FGBD) run notably better. Drain pump and water inlet valve are standard wear items across all tiers.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="appliance-card">
        <h3>Frigidaire Ranges (FFGF gas, FFEF electric, FGGF Gallery, FPGF Professional)</h3>
        <p>Gas (FFGF, FGGF, FPGF) and electric (FFEF, FGEF) freestanding ranges across all three tiers. Common service: surface igniter (gas, year 4-7), bake/broil element (electric, year 8-12), oven temperature sensor, control board, oven door hinge + spring. Professional pro-style ranges add convection fan motor and infrared broiler service.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="appliance-card">
        <h3>Frigidaire Wall Ovens (FFEW single, FGEW Gallery double)</h3>
        <p>Single (FFEW) and double (FGEW Gallery) wall ovens. Less common in our service mix than freestanding ranges but consistent parts platform, bake/broil element, sensor, control board, latch motor on self-clean models. Hinge + spring service common at year 8-11 on heavy doors.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="appliance-card">
        <h3>Frigidaire Microwaves (FFMV over-the-range, FGMV Gallery)</h3>
        <p>Over-the-range (FFMV, FGMV) and countertop variants. Common service: door switch (3-switch system; one fails, microwave won't start), magnetron, turntable motor, charcoal/grease filters (consumables). Gallery models add convection element complexity.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="appliance-card">
        <h3>Frigidaire Cooktops</h3>
        <p>Gas and electric cooktops in mid-tier and Gallery configurations. Common service: surface igniter (gas), burner switch, infinite-switch control (electric coil). Induction variants are less common in Frigidaire's lineup than in some competitors.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="appliance-card">
        <h3>Frigidaire Wine Coolers &amp; Beverage Centers</h3>
        <p>Frigidaire makes a respectable wine cooler and beverage center line (FFWC, FRBG variants). Common service: thermoelectric module (smaller units), compressor/sealed system (larger units), door gasket, control board. Wine cooler service is a specialty subcategory; we dispatch wine-trained techs.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 05 ERROR CODES -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">05, Frigidaire error codes decoded</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">What the codes on your Frigidaire actually mean.</h2>

    <p>Frigidaire's E-series and EF-series error codes are notably direct, each code points to a specific subsystem. Common ones we translate on every service visit:</p>

    <div class="error-table">
      <div class="error-row"><strong>E10</strong>, Water doesn't enter (washer). Inlet valve, supply taps, or hose.</div>
      <div class="error-row"><strong>E20</strong>, Water doesn't drain (washer). Drain pump, hose, or filter.</div>
      <div class="error-row"><strong>E30</strong>, Drum overfilled (washer). Stuck inlet solenoid or level sensor.</div>
      <div class="error-row"><strong>E70</strong>, Cold water doesn't enter (washer). Cold-side inlet valve fault.</div>
      <div class="error-row"><strong>E90 / E91</strong>, Communication fault between control modules (washer).</div>
      <div class="error-row"><strong>EF0</strong>, Over-sudsing (washer). Use less detergent; switch to HE.</div>
      <div class="error-row"><strong>EF1</strong>, Drain pump fault (condenser dryer). Pump clog or sensor.</div>
      <div class="error-row"><strong>EF2</strong>, Too much soap (washer). Reduce dose.</div>
      <div class="error-row"><strong>SY EF</strong>, System fault (varies by model). Reset; if persistent, control board.</div>
      <div class="error-row"><strong>F1 (oven/range)</strong>, Control board fault. Reset clears 10%; balance is board.</div>
      <div class="error-row"><strong>F3 (oven)</strong>, Oven temperature sensor fault.</div>
      <div class="error-row"><strong>F7 (oven)</strong>, Stuck function key on keypad.</div>
      <div class="error-row"><strong>HI (refrigerator)</strong>, Temperature too high. Door, gasket, or cooling system.</div>
      <div class="error-row"><strong>SY CE (refrigerator)</strong>, Communication error between main and door boards.</div>
      <div class="error-row"><strong>OP (refrigerator)</strong>, Open thermistor. Sensor or harness.</div>
    </div>

    <p>Reset procedure for any Frigidaire appliance showing an error: kill the breaker for a full 5 minutes (longer than most appliances need to fully discharge filter capacitors). About 15-20% of error codes clear at this step at no parts cost. If the code returns, that's the diagnostic.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 06 MODELS -->
<section class="section section-gray">
